Question: Do you have any additional ideas, concerns, or feedback you would like to share to help ACME better serve the public?

Response ID: resp_1101
Response Text: Start by listening — really listening — to the artists, organizers, and cultural workers who have been doing this work long before ACME existed. Don’t assume alignment. Don’t extract ideas or stories to justify top-down decisions. Build trust through direct relationships, transparent processes, and redistribution of power and resources.

If ACME wants to serve the public, it needs to be accountable to the public — especially those most impacted by displacement, erasure, and underinvestment. That means centering BIPOC, working-class, disabled, immigrant, and queer artists — not just checking boxes or putting them on panels.

Trust what’s already here. Fund what’s already working. And don’t create new structures that bury the ones we’ve been trying to keep alive.

Extract comprehensive features following the schema.

